### Analysis of Visualization 1
This chart visualizes Bigfoot sightings by state and season. I wanted to show which states have the most activity and identify seasonal patterns. This chart helps demonstrate potential environmental preferences, as sighting frequency varies by season. I used **Nominal** encodings for the state and season categories and **Quantitative** encodings for the record counts. I utilized Altair's internal aggregation to calculate these counts directly from the raw data.

### Analysis of Visualization 2
This chart visualizes sightings by geographical location (longitude and latitude) categorized by season. This spatial view shows which specific regions have the highest density of reports. I used **Quantitative** encodings for the geographic coordinates and **Nominal** encodings for the seasons. No specific custom color scheme was chosen; I utilized Altair's default categorical colors to ensure the seasons remain easy to distinguish. 

### Interactivity Discussion
For the second chart, I implemented a **dropdown menu** that allows users to filter sightings by season. Because the dataset contains a high volume of points, the map can become cluttered. This custom interactivity helps make the visualization clearer by allowing the viewer to focus on one season at a time, providing a better understanding of Bigfoot report distribution.

